        <h1 id="assess">General Assessments</h1>
        <p>
          Warhammer, and in particular Warhammer 2, as a rule set has
          many genre-specific rules, that will not interest us here.
          As an example take Insanity Points.  We are only interested
          in resolving skill rolls and conflicts in general.  We leave
          the genre rules untouched, For instance, the guild structure
          can be added on top.
        </p>
        <p>
          When applying our meta-rule &#8212; <em>10 points difference
          grant a <n10/>:<n1/> chance of winning</em> &#8212; we find
          that Warhammer provides approximately 4 levels.  There are a
          lot of generalizations happening here, but basically these
          levels are at <n5/>%, <em>34</em>%, <em>84</em>% and
          <em>95</em>%.  The most activity being in the middle range,
          we conclude that a +<n5/>% bonus should be a +<n1/> in our
          skill charts.  Of course, at the edge of the scale<s0/>,
          such a bonus is vastly more important.  The purpose of these
          rules is to weed out such discrepencies.
        </p>
        <p>
          To distinguish between this rules set and the Warhammer 2
          rules, we put a subscript <n0/> to the original rules, like
          &#8220;rules<s0/>&#8221;.  The rules we describe here do not
          get a subscript.
        </p>
        <p>
          We <em>normalize</em> any skill with respect to an
          uneducated, uncivilized, but healthy human of about 20-30
          years of age without any training whatsoever.  He has no
          equipment and only simple clothing.  He is called the
          &#8220;N&#8221;ormalized &#8220;N&#8221;obody, <em>NN</em>
          for short.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="container">
        <h1 id="skills">Skills</h1>
        <p>
          All skills<s0/> listed in the rulebook are skills in this
          sense.  Additionally, all attributes<s0/> that are measured
          <n0/>-<n100/>, such as <em>WS</em>, are skills.  The
          remainder of attributes<s0/> are not used (as such).
        </p>
        <p>
          Skill Tests according to the descriptive levels in the
          book<s0/> are <em>Very Easy&#160;(-20), Easy&#160;(-10),
          Routine&#160;(0), Average&#160;(10), Challenging&#160;(20),
          Hard&#160;(30), Very Hard&#160;(40)</em>.  Note that any
          difference of <n20/> is regularly not worth rolling.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some skills are explained in descriptive levels.  Some are
          grouped, where practical.
        </p>
        <h3 id="acare">Animal Care</h3>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN knows the uses and obvious differences
            between domestic animals.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, proper food for an
            animal are known.  The well-being can be discerned and
            fostered.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> Common illnesses of the various domestic
            animals are known, as well treatment thereof.  Moods can
            easily be subdued or provoked.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Caring for animals is second nature.
            Esoteric conditions can be detected and possibly treated.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="atrain">Animal Training</h3>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN knows animals that can be trained and
            the general abilities of such animals.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, simple training methods
            for many animals are known.  The success can be gauged and
            &#8220;tricks&#8221; trained that way.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> Complex training methods for animals are
            known, as well as special abilities that can be harnessed
            thereby.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> At this stage, anything that can be
            trained by humans is possible.  Even to more exotic
            animals.  New techniques may be developped.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="charm">Charm Skills</h3>
        <p>
          Understanding animals or humans as a skill works in the same
          scales, even though the mechanisms are different.  Some
          applications of the skill require additional "investments",
          for example providing food or mutual touch.  These skills
          can be used without consciously (actively) doing so.
        </p>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN can say that obvious markings belong to
            a trail or not.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> At this level, recent, normal trails of
            medium-sized (or larger) animals may be followed.  Small
            markings within sensory range can be identified as
            belonging together.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> Small animal trails, older trails, or
            irregular trails may be followed.  Different type of
            markings and behavioral guesses of the quarry aid in
            extending a trail.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Almost all markings, even miniscule and
            ephemeral, are noticed and incorporated into useful
            estimates of behavior.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="trail">Follow Trail</h3>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN barely knows that a domain for such
            knowledge exists.  With some luck, he can guess whether a
            general topic belongs to that domain or not.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, the basic concepts are
            known, the more esoteric concepts have been heard of but
            cannot be applied.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> All concepts of the domain are known and
            can be applied with confidence.  There are only a few
            topics escaping the grasps of this expert.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Mastery of the subject matter as far as
            humanly possible.  Genuine research or creation of new
            substance is possible.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="trail">Gamble</h3>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN can differentiate between games of
            chance, intellect, and skill.  (This does not mean he can
            identify them correctly.)
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With a few games played, probabilities
            can be gauged and reasonably successful strategies can be
            devised.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> Obscure rules can be used to your
            advantage, strategies are almost optimal, and
            sleight-of-hand tricks may be applied.  (Particularly the
            latter may be dangerous.)
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Professional understanding of games of
            chance, including all &#8220;tricks in the book&#8221;,
            which may be applied.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3 id="know">Knowledge Skills</h3>
        <p>
          All knowledge skills work in the same manner, regardless of
          how difficult it is to achieve a certain level of expertise.
          Keep in mind the meta-rule from the introduction.
          <em>Evaluate</em> is also a knowledge skill.
        </p>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN barely knows that a domain for such
            knowledge exists.  With some luck, he can guess whether a
            general topic belongs to that domain or not.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, the basic concepts are
            known, the more esoteric concepts have been heard of but
            cannot be applied.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> All concepts of the domain are known and
            can be applied with confidence.  There are only a few
